{"test_cases_lookup_map": {"{\"actual_output\": \"The CIS Critical Security Controls (CIS Controls) are a set of security controls developed by a collaborative effort of experts from various sectors and roles to help enterprises defend against common cyber-attacks. They were created to provide constructive action for defenders and share knowledge with a wider audience.\", \"context\": [\"CIS would like to thank the many security experts who volunteer their time and talent to support the CIS Critical Security Controls\\u00ae (CIS Controls\\u00ae) and other CIS work. CIS products represent the effort of a veritable army of volunteers from across the industry, generously giving their time and talent in the name of a more secure online experience for everyone.\", \"The CIS Controls reflect the combined knowledge of experts from every part of the ecosystem (companies, governments, individuals), with every role (threat responders and analysts, technologists, information technology (IT) operators and defenders, vulnerability-finders, tool makers, solution providers, users, policy-makers, auditors, etc.), and across many sectors (government, power, defense, finance, transportation, academia, consulting, security, IT, etc.), who have banded together to create, adopt, and support the CIS Controls.\", \"The CIS Critical Security Controls\\u00ae (CIS Controls\\u00ae) started as a simple grassroots activity to identify the most common and important real-world cyber-attacks that affect enterprises every day, translate that knowledge and experience into positive, constructive action for defenders, and then share that information with a wider audience. The original goals were modest\\u2014to help people and enterprises focus their attention and get started on the most important steps to defend themselves from the attacks that really mattered.\"], \"expected_output\": \"The CIS Controls are critical security controls that help enterprises focus on important steps to defend themselves from common real-world cyberattacks. They reflect the combined knowledge and experience of experts across different sectors, roles, and industries.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"What are CIS Controls?\", \"retrieval_context\": [\"CIS would like to thank the many security experts who volunteer their time and talent to support the CIS Critical Security Controls\\u00ae (CIS Controls\\u00ae) and other CIS work. CIS products represent the effort of a veritable army of volunteers from across the industry, generously giving their time and talent in the name of a more secure online experience for everyone.\", \"The CIS Controls reflect the combined knowledge of experts from every part of the ecosystem (companies, governments, individuals), with every role (threat responders and analysts, technologists, information technology (IT) operators and defenders, vulnerability-finders, tool makers, solution providers, users, policy-makers, auditors, etc.), and across many sectors (government, power, defense, finance, transportation, academia, consulting, security, IT, etc.), who have banded together to create, adopt, and support the CIS Controls.\", \"The CIS Critical Security Controls\\u00ae (CIS Controls\\u00ae) started as a simple grassroots activity to identify the most common and important real-world cyber-attacks that affect enterprises every day, translate that knowledge and experience into positive, constructive action for defenders, and then share that information with a wider audience. The original goals were modest\\u2014to help people and enterprises focus their attention and get started on the most important steps to defend themselves from the attacks that really mattered.\"]}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Hallucination", "threshold": 0.5, "success": false, "score": 0.6666666666666666, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "llama3.2:3b (Ollama)", "evaluationCost": 0, "verboseLogs": "Verdicts:\n[\n    {\n        \"verdict\": \"no\",\n        \"reason\": \"The actual output contradicts the provided context which states that CIS Controls started as a simple grassroots activity, whereas the actual output suggests a collaborative effort of experts from various sectors and roles.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"verdict\": \"yes\",\n        \"reason\": \"The actual output agrees with the provided context which states that CIS Controls were created to provide constructive action for defenders and share knowledge with a wider audience.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"verdict\": \"no\",\n        \"reason\": \"The actual output contradicts the provided context which states that CIS products represent the effort of a veritable army of volunteers, whereas the actual output does not mention volunteers or an 'army' of people.\"\n    }\n]"}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.5, "evaluation_model": "llama3.2:3b (Ollama)", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": false}}]}, "{\"actual_output\": \"The CIS Controls were created to identify the most common and important real-world cyber-attacks that affect enterprises every day. The original goals were modest\\u2014to help people and enterprises focus their attention on the most important steps to defend themselves from the attacks that really mattered.\", \"context\": [\"The CIS Controls reflect the combined knowledge of experts from every part of the ecosystem (companies, governments, individuals), with every role (threat responders and analysts, technologists, information technology (IT) operators and defenders, vulnerability-finders, tool makers, solution providers, users, policy-makers, auditors, etc.), and across many sectors (government, power, defense, finance, transportation, academia, consulting, security, IT, etc.), who have banded together to create, adopt, and support the CIS Controls.\", \"The CIS Controls started like many similar activities; we gathered experts together, and shared and argued until we reached an agreement. This can be very valuable, depending on the people at the table and their experience. Through documenting and sharing the output, all enterprises can benefit from the work of people they cannot hire or even meet. You can improve the outcome (and your confidence in it) through selecting experts that represent a wide range of knowledge, bringing consistency to the process, and ensuring use of the best-available information (especially about attacks). In the end, you are still depending on the good judgment of a relatively small group of people, captured in an informal and narrative way.\", \"The CIS Critical Security Controls\\u00ae (CIS Controls\\u00ae) started as a simple grassroots activity to identify the most common and important real-world cyber-attacks that affect enterprises every day, translate that knowledge and experience into positive, constructive action for defenders, and then share that information with a wider audience. The original goals were modest\\u2014to help people and enterprises focus their attention and get started on the most important steps to defend themselves from the attacks that really mattered.\"], \"expected_output\": \"They were created to help people and enterprises focus on the most important steps needed to defend themselves from real-world cyberattacks.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"Why were the CIS Controls created?\", \"retrieval_context\": [\"The CIS Controls reflect the combined knowledge of experts from every part of the ecosystem (companies, governments, individuals), with every role (threat responders and analysts, technologists, information technology (IT) operators and defenders, vulnerability-finders, tool makers, solution providers, users, policy-makers, auditors, etc.), and across many sectors (government, power, defense, finance, transportation, academia, consulting, security, IT, etc.), who have banded together to create, adopt, and support the CIS Controls.\", \"The CIS Controls started like many similar activities; we gathered experts together, and shared and argued until we reached an agreement. This can be very valuable, depending on the people at the table and their experience. Through documenting and sharing the output, all enterprises can benefit from the work of people they cannot hire or even meet. You can improve the outcome (and your confidence in it) through selecting experts that represent a wide range of knowledge, bringing consistency to the process, and ensuring use of the best-available information (especially about attacks). In the end, you are still depending on the good judgment of a relatively small group of people, captured in an informal and narrative way.\", \"The CIS Critical Security Controls\\u00ae (CIS Controls\\u00ae) started as a simple grassroots activity to identify the most common and important real-world cyber-attacks that affect enterprises every day, translate that knowledge and experience into positive, constructive action for defenders, and then share that information with a wider audience. The original goals were modest\\u2014to help people and enterprises focus their attention and get started on the most important steps to defend themselves from the attacks that really mattered.\"]}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Hallucination", "threshold": 0.5, "success": true, "score": 0.3333333333333333, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "llama3.2:3b (Ollama)", "evaluationCost": 0, "verboseLogs": "Verdicts:\n[\n    {\n        \"verdict\": \"yes\",\n        \"reason\": \"The actual output agrees with the provided context which states that The CIS Controls were created to identify the most common and important real-world cyber-attacks that affect enterprises every day.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"verdict\": \"no\",\n        \"reason\": \"The actual output contradicts the provided context which states that The CIS Controls started as a simple grassroots activity, whereas the actual output only mentions creation of the controls without mentioning their origin.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"verdict\": \"yes\",\n        \"reason\": \"The actual output agrees with the provided context which states that The original goals were modest\\u2014to help people and enterprises focus their attention on the most important steps to defend themselves from the attacks that really mattered.\"\n    }\n]"}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.5, "evaluation_model": "llama3.2:3b (Ollama)", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": false}}]}, "{\"actual_output\": \"The CIS Controls reflect the combined knowledge of experts from various roles, sectors, and parts of the ecosystem. CIS products represent the effort of volunteers from across the industry who generously give their time and talent to support the CIS Critical Security Controls.\", \"context\": [\"CIS would like to thank the many security experts who volunteer their time and talent to support the CIS Critical Security Controls\\u00ae (CIS Controls\\u00ae) and other CIS work. CIS products represent the effort of a veritable army of volunteers from across the industry, generously giving their time and talent in the name of a more secure online experience for everyone.\", \"The CIS Controls reflect the combined knowledge of experts from every part of the ecosystem (companies, governments, individuals), with every role (threat responders and analysts, technologists, information technology (IT) operators and defenders, vulnerability-finders, tool makers, solution providers, users, policy-makers, auditors, etc.), and across many sectors (government, power, defense, finance, transportation, academia, consulting, security, IT, etc.), who have banded together to create, adopt, and support the CIS Controls.\", \"The CIS Critical Security Controls\\u00ae (CIS Controls\\u00ae) started as a simple grassroots activity to identify the most common and important real-world cyber-attacks that affect enterprises every day, translate that knowledge and experience into positive, constructive action for defenders, and then share that information with a wider audience. The original goals were modest\\u2014to help people and enterprises focus their attention and get started on the most important steps to defend themselves from the attacks that really mattered.\"], \"expected_output\": \"The CIS Controls are supported by experts from many parts of the cybersecurity ecosystem, including governments, companies, threat responders, IT defenders, auditors, policy-makers, and solution providers.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"Who contributes to the CIS Controls?\", \"retrieval_context\": [\"CIS would like to thank the many security experts who volunteer their time and talent to support the CIS Critical Security Controls\\u00ae (CIS Controls\\u00ae) and other CIS work. CIS products represent the effort of a veritable army of volunteers from across the industry, generously giving their time and talent in the name of a more secure online experience for everyone.\", \"The CIS Controls reflect the combined knowledge of experts from every part of the ecosystem (companies, governments, individuals), with every role (threat responders and analysts, technologists, information technology (IT) operators and defenders, vulnerability-finders, tool makers, solution providers, users, policy-makers, auditors, etc.), and across many sectors (government, power, defense, finance, transportation, academia, consulting, security, IT, etc.), who have banded together to create, adopt, and support the CIS Controls.\", \"The CIS Critical Security Controls\\u00ae (CIS Controls\\u00ae) started as a simple grassroots activity to identify the most common and important real-world cyber-attacks that affect enterprises every day, translate that knowledge and experience into positive, constructive action for defenders, and then share that information with a wider audience. The original goals were modest\\u2014to help people and enterprises focus their attention and get started on the most important steps to defend themselves from the attacks that really mattered.\"]}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Answer Relevancy", "threshold": 0.5, "success": true, "score": 0.5, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "llama3.2:3b (Ollama)", "evaluationCost": 0.0, "verboseLogs": "Statements:\n[\n    \"The CIS Controls reflect the combined knowledge of experts from various roles, sectors, and parts of the ecosystem.\",\n    \"CIS products represent the effort of volunteers from across the industry who generously give their time and talent to support the CIS Critical Security Controls.\"\n] \n \nVerdicts:\n[\n    {\n        \"verdict\": \"yes\",\n        \"reason\": null\n    },\n    {\n        \"verdict\": \"no\",\n        \"reason\": \"The statement does not directly answer the question about who contributes to the CIS Controls.\"\n    }\n]"}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.5, "evaluation_model": "llama3.2:3b (Ollama)", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": false}}, {"metric_data": {"name": "Contextual Precision", "threshold": 0.5, "success": true, "score": 1.0, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "llama3.2:3b (Ollama)", "evaluationCost": 0.0, "verboseLogs": "Verdicts:\n[\n    {\n        \"verdict\": \"yes\",\n        \"reason\": \"The text clearly addresses the question by stating that 'The CIS Controls are supported by experts from many parts of the cybersecurity ecosystem, including governments, companies, threat responders, IT defenders, auditors, policy-makers, and solution providers.'\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"verdict\": \"yes\",\n        \"reason\": \"It verifies that the CIS Controls are indeed supported by a wide range of experts across various sectors.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"verdict\": \"no\",\n        \"reason\": \"'The CIS Critical Security Controls started as a simple grassroots activity' does not address the question about who contributes to the CIS Controls, and instead talks about their origins.\"\n    }\n]"}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.5, "evaluation_model": "llama3.2:3b (Ollama)", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": false}}, {"metric_data": {"name": "Hallucination", "threshold": 0.5, "success": true, "score": 0.3333333333333333, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "llama3.2:3b (Ollama)", "evaluationCost": 0.0, "verboseLogs": "Verdicts:\n[\n    {\n        \"verdict\": \"yes\",\n        \"reason\": \"The actual output agrees with the provided context which states that the CIS Controls reflect the combined knowledge of experts from various roles, sectors, and parts of the ecosystem.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"verdict\": \"no\",\n        \"reason\": \"The actual output contradicts the provided context by stating 'various' instead of 'every', which implies a difference in scope or detail.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"verdict\": \"yes\",\n        \"reason\": \"The actual output agrees with the provided context which states that CIS products represent the effort of volunteers from across the industry who generously give their time and talent to support the CIS Critical Security Controls.\"\n    }\n]"}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.5, "evaluation_model": "llama3.2:3b (Ollama)", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": false}}]}, "{\"actual_output\": \"The CIS Controls were created to identify the most common and important real-world cyber-attacks that affect enterprises every day. The purpose of CIS Controls v8 is to provide a set of critical security controls to help defenders focus their attention on the most important steps to defend themselves from these attacks.\", \"context\": [\"The CIS Controls reflect the combined knowledge of experts from every part of the ecosystem (companies, governments, individuals), with every role (threat responders and analysts, technologists, information technology (IT) operators and defenders, vulnerability-finders, tool makers, solution providers, users, policy-makers, auditors, etc.), and across many sectors (government, power, defense, finance, transportation, academia, consulting, security, IT, etc.), who have banded together to create, adopt, and support the CIS Controls.\", \"The CIS Critical Security Controls\\u00ae (CIS Controls\\u00ae) started as a simple grassroots activity to identify the most common and important real-world cyber-attacks that affect enterprises every day, translate that knowledge and experience into positive, constructive action for defenders, and then share that information with a wider audience. The original goals were modest\\u2014to help people and enterprises focus their attention and get started on the most important steps to defend themselves from the attacks that really mattered.\", \"To support this, CIS acts as a catalyst and clearinghouse to help us all learn from each other. Since Version 6, there has been an explosion of complementary information, products, and services available from CIS, and from the industry-at-large. Please contact CIS for the following kinds of working aids and other support materials, https://www.cisecurity.org/controls/v8/:\"], \"expected_output\": \"The purpose of CIS Controls v8 is to guide organizations in implementing, measuring, reporting, and managing enterprise security through clear and practical safeguards.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"What is the purpose of CIS Controls v8?\", \"retrieval_context\": [\"The CIS Controls reflect the combined knowledge of experts from every part of the ecosystem (companies, governments, individuals), with every role (threat responders and analysts, technologists, information technology (IT) operators and defenders, vulnerability-finders, tool makers, solution providers, users, policy-makers, auditors, etc.), and across many sectors (government, power, defense, finance, transportation, academia, consulting, security, IT, etc.), who have banded together to create, adopt, and support the CIS Controls.\", \"The CIS Critical Security Controls\\u00ae (CIS Controls\\u00ae) started as a simple grassroots activity to identify the most common and important real-world cyber-attacks that affect enterprises every day, translate that knowledge and experience into positive, constructive action for defenders, and then share that information with a wider audience. The original goals were modest\\u2014to help people and enterprises focus their attention and get started on the most important steps to defend themselves from the attacks that really mattered.\", \"To support this, CIS acts as a catalyst and clearinghouse to help us all learn from each other. Since Version 6, there has been an explosion of complementary information, products, and services available from CIS, and from the industry-at-large. Please contact CIS for the following kinds of working aids and other support materials, https://www.cisecurity.org/controls/v8/:\"]}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Contextual Recall", "threshold": 0.5, "success": true, "score": 1.0, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "llama3.2:3b (Ollama)", "evaluationCost": 0, "verboseLogs": "Verdicts:\n[\n    {\n        \"verdict\": \"yes\",\n        \"reason\": \"The sentence can be attributed to the 1st node in the retrieval context, which mentions 'CIS Critical Security Controls' and provides a brief overview of its purpose.\",\n        \"expected_output\": \"The purpose of CIS Controls v8 is to guide organizations in implementing, measuring, reporting, and managing enterprise security through clear and practical safeguards.\"\n    }\n]"}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.5, "evaluation_model": "llama3.2:3b (Ollama)", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": false}}]}, "{\"actual_output\": \"The CIS Controls in Version 8 use revised terminology and grouping of safeguards because, historically, the original sequence proved to be too simplistic for enterprises, especially small ones, which could struggle with implementing early Safeguards. As a result, Implementation Groups (IGs) were introduced to prioritize implementation, providing a more tailored approach for different types of enterprises.\", \"context\": [\"Historically, the CIS Controls were ordered in sequence to focus an enterprise\\u2019s cybersecurity activities, with a subset of the first six CIS Controls referred to as \\u201ccyber hygiene.\\u201d However, this proved to be too simplistic. Enterprises, especially small ones, could struggle with some of the early Safeguards and never get around to implementing later CIS Controls (for example, having a backup strategy to help recover from ransomware). As a result, starting with Version 7.1, we created CIS Controls Implementation Groups (IGs) as our recommended new guidance to prioritize implementation.\", \"How to Get Started Using or Transitioning from Prior Versions of the CIS Controls Structure of the CIS Controls Implementation Groups Control 01 Inventory and Control of Enterprise Assets ............................................................ 7 Why is this Control critical? Procedures and tools Safeguards Control 02 Inventory and Control of Software Assets ............................................................ 10 Why is this Control critical? Procedures and tools Safeguards Control 03 Data Protection ................................................................................................... 13 Why is this Control critical? Procedures and tools Safeguards Control 04 Secure Configuration of Enterprise Assets and Software ..................................... 16 Why is this Control critical? Procedures and tools Safeguards Control 05 Account Management ......................................................................................... 19 Why is this Control\", \"The CIS Controls IGs are self-assessed categories for enterprises. Each IG identifies a subset of the CIS Controls that the community has broadly assessed to be applicable for an enterprise with a similar risk profile and resources to strive to implement. These IGs represent a horizontal look across the CIS Controls tailored to different types of enterprises. Specifically, we have defined IG1 as \\u201cessential cyber hygiene,\\u201d the foundational set of cyber defense Safeguards that every enterprise should apply to guard against the most common attacks (https://www.cisecurity.org/controls/v8/). Each IG then builds upon the previous one: IG2 includes IG1, and IG3 includes all CIS Safeguards in IG1 and IG2.\"], \"expected_output\": \"CIS Controls v8 uses revised terminology and grouping of safeguards to reflect changes in technology and cybersecurity, including cloud computing, virtualization, mobility, outsourcing, work-from-home, and changing attacker tactics.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"Why does CIS Controls v8 use revised terminology and grouping of safeguards?\", \"retrieval_context\": [\"Historically, the CIS Controls were ordered in sequence to focus an enterprise\\u2019s cybersecurity activities, with a subset of the first six CIS Controls referred to as \\u201ccyber hygiene.\\u201d However, this proved to be too simplistic. Enterprises, especially small ones, could struggle with some of the early Safeguards and never get around to implementing later CIS Controls (for example, having a backup strategy to help recover from ransomware). As a result, starting with Version 7.1, we created CIS Controls Implementation Groups (IGs) as our recommended new guidance to prioritize implementation.\", \"How to Get Started Using or Transitioning from Prior Versions of the CIS Controls Structure of the CIS Controls Implementation Groups Control 01 Inventory and Control of Enterprise Assets ............................................................ 7 Why is this Control critical? Procedures and tools Safeguards Control 02 Inventory and Control of Software Assets ............................................................ 10 Why is this Control critical? Procedures and tools Safeguards Control 03 Data Protection ................................................................................................... 13 Why is this Control critical? Procedures and tools Safeguards Control 04 Secure Configuration of Enterprise Assets and Software ..................................... 16 Why is this Control critical? Procedures and tools Safeguards Control 05 Account Management ......................................................................................... 19 Why is this Control\", \"The CIS Controls IGs are self-assessed categories for enterprises. Each IG identifies a subset of the CIS Controls that the community has broadly assessed to be applicable for an enterprise with a similar risk profile and resources to strive to implement. These IGs represent a horizontal look across the CIS Controls tailored to different types of enterprises. Specifically, we have defined IG1 as \\u201cessential cyber hygiene,\\u201d the foundational set of cyber defense Safeguards that every enterprise should apply to guard against the most common attacks (https://www.cisecurity.org/controls/v8/). Each IG then builds upon the previous one: IG2 includes IG1, and IG3 includes all CIS Safeguards in IG1 and IG2.\"]}": {"cached_metrics_data": []}, "{\"actual_output\": \"The CIS Controls reflect the combined knowledge of experts from various roles, sectors, and individuals who have banded together to create, adopt, and support the CIS Controls. CIS products represent the effort of volunteers from across the industry, generously giving their time and talent in the name of a more secure online experience for everyone.\", \"context\": [\"CIS would like to thank the many security experts who volunteer their time and talent to support the CIS Critical Security Controls\\u00ae (CIS Controls\\u00ae) and other CIS work. CIS products represent the effort of a veritable army of volunteers from across the industry, generously giving their time and talent in the name of a more secure online experience for everyone.\", \"The CIS Controls reflect the combined knowledge of experts from every part of the ecosystem (companies, governments, individuals), with every role (threat responders and analysts, technologists, information technology (IT) operators and defenders, vulnerability-finders, tool makers, solution providers, users, policy-makers, auditors, etc.), and across many sectors (government, power, defense, finance, transportation, academia, consulting, security, IT, etc.), who have banded together to create, adopt, and support the CIS Controls.\", \"The CIS Critical Security Controls\\u00ae (CIS Controls\\u00ae) started as a simple grassroots activity to identify the most common and important real-world cyber-attacks that affect enterprises every day, translate that knowledge and experience into positive, constructive action for defenders, and then share that information with a wider audience. The original goals were modest\\u2014to help people and enterprises focus their attention and get started on the most important steps to defend themselves from the attacks that really mattered.\"], \"expected_output\": \"The CIS Controls are supported by experts from many parts of the cybersecurity ecosystem, including governments, companies, threat responders, IT defenders, auditors, policy-makers, and solution providers.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"Who contributes to the CIS Controls?\", \"retrieval_context\": [\"CIS would like to thank the many security experts who volunteer their time and talent to support the CIS Critical Security Controls\\u00ae (CIS Controls\\u00ae) and other CIS work. CIS products represent the effort of a veritable army of volunteers from across the industry, generously giving their time and talent in the name of a more secure online experience for everyone.\", \"The CIS Controls reflect the combined knowledge of experts from every part of the ecosystem (companies, governments, individuals), with every role (threat responders and analysts, technologists, information technology (IT) operators and defenders, vulnerability-finders, tool makers, solution providers, users, policy-makers, auditors, etc.), and across many sectors (government, power, defense, finance, transportation, academia, consulting, security, IT, etc.), who have banded together to create, adopt, and support the CIS Controls.\", \"The CIS Critical Security Controls\\u00ae (CIS Controls\\u00ae) started as a simple grassroots activity to identify the most common and important real-world cyber-attacks that affect enterprises every day, translate that knowledge and experience into positive, constructive action for defenders, and then share that information with a wider audience. The original goals were modest\\u2014to help people and enterprises focus their attention and get started on the most important steps to defend themselves from the attacks that really mattered.\"]}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Hallucination", "threshold": 0.5, "success": true, "score": 0.3333333333333333, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "llama3.2:3b (Ollama)", "evaluationCost": 0, "verboseLogs": "Verdicts:\n[\n    {\n        \"verdict\": \"yes\",\n        \"reason\": \"The actual output agrees with the provided context which states that CIS Controls reflect the combined knowledge of experts from various roles, sectors, and individuals who have banded together to create, adopt, and support the CIS Controls.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"verdict\": \"no\",\n        \"reason\": \"The actual output contradicts the provided context which states that CIS products represent the effort of a veritable army of volunteers from across the industry, generously giving their time and talent in the name of a more secure online experience for everyone. Instead, it says volunteers from across the industry.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"verdict\": \"yes\",\n        \"reason\": \"The actual output agrees with the provided context which states that CIS Critical Security Controls started as a simple grassroots activity to identify common and important real-world cyber-attacks, translate that knowledge into positive action for defenders, and share information with a wider audience.\"\n    }\n]"}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.5, "evaluation_model": "llama3.2:3b (Ollama)", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": false}}]}}}